<p>
    <div id="accordion">
        <h5>About LoanBender</h5>
        <div>
            LoanBender is an advanced amortization calculator that gives you accelerated pay-off dates that take into account extra principle payments that vary over the course of the loan term.<br /><br />
            Most mortgage calculators assume that your extra principle payments will be constant.  But lenders typically don't care how much you apply to the principal each month.  Your payments may vary, depending on your circumstances.  LoanBender is an loan calculator that gives you the flexibility of changing the monthly amount you might pay toward the principle at any given month, and shows you the affect throughout the term of the loan instantly!<br /><br />

        </div>
        <h5>How Pay-Off Acceleration Works</h5>
        <div>
            If an extra payment is made to pay off a loan or mortgage, the payment reduces the remaining balance by that amount. Consequently, the balance at the end of the term will be that much less.<br /><br />
            Run the calculation for any loan and look at the amount of the principle on the last line of the amortization table. Notice that amount of the principle is almost equal to the amount of whole monthly payment. This means that at anytime, if you make an extra payment that is equal to the amount of your monthly payment, you will shorten the term of your loan by one month.<br /><br />
            If many extra payments are made, it will shorten the term significantly.<br /><br />
        </div>
        <h5>What is required?</h5>
        <div>
            “Interest Rate” has two drop-down menues, one for choosing whole percent values and the other for fractional values. <br /><br />
            “Loan Amount” is the total amount that was borrowed. By the way, LoanBender can be used with any type of currency. Just ignore all references to dollars and use your currency of choice (without the symbol) for Loan Amount and Monthly Tax / Insurance.  <br /><br />
            The “Term” is the length of time in years of the original payment plan, or how long it would take to pay off the loan if no additional money was put toward the priniciple.  Just as the loan amount does not change, this number does not change either. <br /><br />
            The “Monthly Tax And/Or Insurance” entry applies mostly to mortgages.  It does not enter into the pay-off calculation; it only affects the monthly Total Mortgage Payment column in the table.  If you have a mortgage, enter your monthly property tax escrow payment plus your monthly mortgage insurance premium.  If your loan payment does not have any such additional charges, this value can be zero.<br /><br />
            The “Starting Month” and “Starting Year” is the month and year that the loan commenced (when you began making payments).  This starting date can be in the future, but the “Current Date” cannot be earlier than the starting date (that would not make any sense!). <br /><br />
            The “Current Date” is the date from which you want to begin your analysis.  It will be the month and year of the first row of the amortization table. <br /><br />
        </div>
        <h5>How LoanBender Can Be Used</h5>
        <div>
            LoanBender can work with any kind of loan or mortgage - second mortgage, student loan, or car loan.  Just enter the details of the loan and hit “Submit”.<br /><br />
            LoanBender is an educational tool that demonstrates how quickly a loan can be paid-off for different scenarios.  One thing it can show is if there would be an affect on the pay-off date if you put more money in towards one end of the term as opposed to the other end.<br /><br />
            What if you wanted to see how much sooner your loan would be paid off if you could put more money toward the principle at some time in the future.  You would first enter the details of your loan and select “Submit” to display the amortization table. Then just scroll down to the month you anticipate making the new additional payment, enter that amount under the “Additional Principle Payment” column, and select “From Here”.  The table will then repopulate displaying a new amortization table accounting for the new amount beginning at that month and continuing all the way to the end of the term.  You can enter different amounts at different months for any number of months, too.<br /><br />
        </div>
    </div>
</p>

